  "response_text": "The average weekly consumption of skimmed and semi-skimmed milk exhibits a pronounced upward trajectory over the course of the simulation. Beginning at a baseline value of 5.29 at time step 0, the metric reflects the initial market dominance of whole milk. A steep increase characterizes the early phase, with consumption rising sharply through time step 9, indicating a rapid initial shift in consumer behavior driven by agent perception and the triggering of disposition to evaluate alternatives. From time step 10 to time step 24, the growth rate decelerates into a period of oscillation around the 1200 mark. Notable fluctuations include a local peak of 1265.47 at time step 11 and a subsequent dip to 1233.62 at time step 12, followed by further variations such as a valley at 1183.39 at time step 18. This middle phase suggests a dynamic equilibrium where habit strength and social influence compete with evolving preferences, temporarily stabilizing adoption rates. After time step 25, the increasing trend resumes. By the final time step, index 32, the mean quantity reaches a maximum of 1456.60. This final value signifies a substantial long-term substitution of whole milk for skimmed and semi-skimmed varieties, illustrating the cumulative impact of social norms and learned experiences on individual decision-making processes within the modeled network."
}

